On February 8, 2016, the President signed three bills into law. The first bill, H.R. 515, known as the "International Megan's Law to Prevent Child Exploitation and Other Sexual Crimes Through Advanced Notification of Traveling Sex Offenders," authorizes the Department of Homeland Security and the Department of Justice to send and receive notifications about registered sex offenders traveling internationally. It also requires the Department of State to include unique identifiers on passports issued to registered sex offenders. 

The second bill, H.R. 4188, called the "Coast Guard Authorization Act of 2015," authorizes appropriations for the Coast Guard for fiscal years 2016 and 2017. It also amends laws related to the Coast Guard and the Federal Maritime Commission.

Lastly, S. 2152, known as the "Electrify Africa Act of 2015," encourages countries in sub-Saharan Africa to improve access to affordable and reliable electricity.